d:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 mb-6 not-prose","children":["$","ul",null,{"className":"space-y-2.5 border-l-4 border-yellow-400/50 pl-4","children":[["$","li","0",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"FBI’s wiretap systems breached, investigation underway"}]]}],["$","li","1",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Unclear if sensitive data was exposed or exploited"}]]}],["$","li","2",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Signal to enterprises: Even top-tier security isn’t bulletproof"}]]}]]}]}]
e:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 article-prose max-w-none","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":["A hack into the FBI’s wiretap and surveillance systems isn’t just another cybersecurity headline—it’s a rare moment where the hunter becomes the hunted. According to ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://edition.cnn.com","children":"CNN’s reporting"}],", the breach is under active investigation, but the details that matter most—",["$","em",null,{"children":"what"}]," was accessed, ",["$","em",null,{"children":"how"}]," it happened, and ",["$","em",null,{"children":"who"}]," is responsible—remain locked behind bureaucratic silence.\nThis isn’t about schadenfreude. It’s a stress test for an industry that sells trust as its core product. The FBI’s systems are, in theory, among the most fortified on the planet. If they’re vulnerable, the message to enterprises is blunt: ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"No one is exempt."}]," The timing is particularly awkward. Just last month, the agency ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.fbi.gov/news/speeches","children":"warned private companies"}]," about rising state-sponsored cyber threats. Now, it’s facing its own reckoning.\nThe practical fallout depends on what was exposed. Wiretap systems don’t just store audio—they log metadata, locations, and connections that could unravel entire investigations if compromised. Early signals suggest the breach may have been contained, but ‘contained’ is a low bar when the stakes include national security. For tech vendors selling to government clients, this is a moment to brace for scrutiny. If the FBI’s tools can be infiltrated, what does that say about the ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.wired.com/tag/surveillance/","children":"commercial surveillance tech"}]," flooding the market?"]}],"\n",["$","div",null,{"className":"not-prose my-8 pt-6 border-t border-white/10","children":[null,["$","div",null,{"className":"glass-card overflow-hidden mb-4 !hover:transform-none","children":["$","img",null,{"src":"/images/articles/fbis-surveillance-hack-more-than-just-a-security-s/subtitle.jpg","alt":"Kada i FBI postane meta, što to znači za vašu sigurnost?","className":"w-full h-auto max-h-[400px] object-cover"}]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-text-secondary italic text-lg leading-relaxed font-medium","children":"Kada i FBI postane meta, što to znači za vašu sigurnost?"}]]}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":["The bigger question isn’t ",["$","em",null,{"children":"if"}]," this changes cybersecurity—it’s ",["$","em",null,{"children":"how much"}],". For years, the industry has operated on the assumption that nation-state actors target everyone ",["$","em",null,{"children":"except"}]," the agencies chasing them. That illusion is now cracked. The immediate ripple effect? Expect federal contractors to face stricter ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.cisa.gov/zero-trust","children":"Zero Trust"}]," mandates, and for cyber insurance premiums to climb as underwriters recalibrate risk models.\nFor everyday users, the breach is a reminder that surveillance tech—whether in government or corporate hands—is only as secure as its weakest link. The FBI’s systems are likely more robust than your average ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://techcrunch.com/tag/enterprise/","children":"enterprise SaaS tool"}],", but the principle holds: ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"Complexity breeds vulnerability."}]," The more data you collect, the more attractive a target you become. That’s a hard pill for companies that have spent years pitching ‘end-to-end encryption’ as a silver bullet.\nWhat’s missing from the conversation? Accountability for the supply chain. If this hack traces back to a third-party vendor (as many breaches do), it’ll expose how little control even the FBI has over its own infrastructure. For now, the agency’s silence speaks volumes. But the real test isn’t how they spin this—it’s whether they’ll demand the same transparency from their tech partners that they enforce on everyone else."]}]]}]
